ranslate? And when they differ, how are their subtleties and complexities understood? In comparing how sexual harassment-a concept that first emerged in 1975-has been defined differently in France and the United States, Abigail Saguy explores not only the social problem of sexual harassment but also the broader cultural concerns of cross-national differences and similarities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHarcèlement sexuelxDroitxFrance. 0aHarcèlement sexuelxDroitxÉtats-Unis. 0aHarcèlement sexuelxFrancexFrancexUnited States. 0aHarcèlement sexuelxÉtats-Unis. 0aSexual harassmentxFrance. 0aSexual harassmentxLaw and legislationxFrance. 0aSexual harassmentxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aSexual harassmentxUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520936973.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles